\nEven after ABS was developed, MLB still wanted human umpires to shout out decisions as they had in their [match]33[/match] . The umpire\'s job had, at one time, required a [match]34[/match] about whether a ball was a strike. A ball is considered a strike when the batter does not hit it and it crosses through a [match]35[/match] extending approximately from the batter\'s knee to his chest.[br][br]\nIn the past, [match]36[/match] over strike calls were not uncommon, but today everyone accepts the complete ban on pushing or shoving the umpire. One difference, however, is that during the first game DeJesus used ABS, strike calls were met with [match]37[/match].', 1, 'Umpires announce the computer\'s call.', NOW());

